so all that code is 'dead code' it will never run, it just sits there. Also let me tell you there is not much original code on the website. The co-ordinates are dead code as well. 
Yeah code might be messy when you first write it, but you don't ship dead code. https://t.co/NSStKhH2SM

so here
1: selects the div with id="door-wrap"
2: selects img in div with id="door"
3: selects where class="frame" in div with id="door"
..and so on, but then we get to
4. selects  where class="drop" in div with id="door"

..except there is no class drop. https://t.co/cKMhvHuLQq

Then another bit controls how the elements you define behave.

They do so by referencing the ids and classes defined in the layout from before.  

for classes we use a dot, so .class
for ids we use # so, # id https://t.co/WaRSm2l4Qm

I'll try to make this as human readable as possible, sorry in advance 😅

It has 4 phots: The door-frame the door-face the background and the floor.

@HLDTour As someone that trains mma, and teaches self defence to women. I personally think this does more harm than good. I think everyone's heart sharing this was in the right place though, but I feel like I have the responsibility to point it out 🤍

https://t.co/E0mhZfA6da

If any of you are actually considering taking up self defence then I'd be more than happy to help you find something  in your area 🤍

Personally I'd always recommend bjj, especially for women. Here is  great article on why.
https://t.co/OTYNDkaisV

Your fourth is to dedicate hours to get your body to respond and move without thinking. Learning and practicing efficient ways to defend yourself. More efficiently surviving, and then as you progress creating a way to escape.

Your second best is to do anything you can to not getting into that situation in the first place. (This sucks, and shouldn't be the case, but it is)

Your third one is to survive. I'm sorry this is brutal. But situations these tips apply to are. Survive until you can get away.

What is worst is that lazy self defence teachings can create a false security/confidence. This is actually very dangerous. Best case this doesn't work, worse it escalates the situation. 

Your best self defence is always not engaging in the first place, and running away. Always.

..and that is if the moves are good. Which the ones I've seen, are not.

I dont want to share examples but
- Grips don't break that easy.
- That will not hurt enough for you to be able to run away.
- That person is not falling.
- They won't give you time to do that.
- No leverage

Even if most of the "moves" I've seen were effective, which they are not, this would still be a horrible idea.

What do you think the odds are that an untrained person would execute a move for the first time correctly in a highly stressful situation.

I'll tell you. Not good.

Why do I have any credit to speak on this? Because I fight people for fun (as a sport), and teach women to defend themselves as well.

I think everyone should practice self defence. Practice being the key word. You don't learn it. You practice it. 
..and photos can't do that.

This has to be said, and since I don't know if anyone else will or has the knowledge to say it, I guess I'll be the one. Just know this comes from a place of love. I believe everyone's heart was in the right place 🤍

But..

tl;dr
- Don't be a dick
- Take responsibility for yourself
- Be respectful of everyone else
- Have a plan for different scenarios that might come up
- Don't be stubborn, don't be stupid, be safe 🤍

Before the pit /geneal:

- Know what your body needs, probably this includes:  eat, drink water, maybe elecrolites / salts

- If your artist knows sign language, maybe learn a few emergency signs

- If you didn't arrive with a friend, consider finding a buddy

Depending on who is most invested in that night's show, there is also a pre decided parent for the night. They will leave no questions asked. If someone needs water, they get it. They have the keys to the car incase its so bad someone needs to get home. This obviously rotates.

My friend can't stay the whole time, at some point they will have to go pee, they always get water on the way back for everyone.

Our tall dude is our guiding light, he is the one that has his phone ready to help guide anyone that may have left back. He is also the one that stays

Before the pit /roles :

- If you are going with friends, have a talk before the show. Know who might have any issue, know who is okay with what, who has what role.

I am often the one who is behind my friends making sure they have space, because I'm okay with being that bitch.

To sum that up:
Take responsibility for yourself. Know yourself and your limits and daily fluctuations. Dont put yourself in situations you can not handle. Make sure your body has the best chance to deal with that situation. Don't be stubborn, don't be stupid, be safe.

- Could be a this time only thing. 

Maybe it's your first time standing at a concert, so ease your way in and stay close to the edges. Next time you know better what to expect and can go further.

Maybe you are alone, normally you'd be in the middle, but this spiked your anxiety

Dont be in the pit if you are not equipped to be there:

- Could be a day by day thing. It is for me. I'm chronically ill, I have good days and bad days, on bad days I  don't go deep into a pit

- Could be a general thing. Easily claustrophobic, prone to fainting etc

- Don't push into the person in front of you, even if it wasn't for covid nobody needs you that close. Only doing it because its being done to you? well, then talk to them..

- If someone asks you to move back, or give them space, you move back  and give them space. That simple.

- Take notice of yourself. Know the signs of dehydration. Be honest with your self about if it safe for you to stay where you are.

- If you do need water, it's your job to get yourself water. You are not glued to the floor, if you don't want to leave, then prepare accordingly.

- Your enjoyment is not worth someone else's suffering. I know its hard to not get lost in the passion, but let's try and make it enjoyable for everyone there.

- Pay attention to the people closest to you, If you can prevent a crises before one happens, it's better for everyone

Once in the pit:

- Map out where you are at, where it would be best for you to exit. What kind of people are around

- Concerts aren't a competition. Be content with whatever spot you got. If the only way you walk away happy is if you clawed your way to the front. Just stay home

Pit Etiquette
+ some concert advice 🙂

Dalí already drew attention as an eccentric and dandy. He had long hair and sideburns, coat, stockings, and knee-breeches in the style of English aesthetes of the late 19th century. 

I think you can guess where this is going. Yes, people speculated about his sexuality.

So let's start with a little background on Dalí.

Major themes in his work include dreams, the subconscious, sexuality, religion, science and his closest personal relationships.

His eccentric and ostentatious public behavior often drew more attention than his artwork

Note that you might not get these exact numbers, as you don't have the same currency conversion rate as me.

(This is not a Pleasing problem, this is a online shopping / currency problem)

So, those changes resulted in: 

Shipping to HC:
$132.42 》$126.6 (listed with s & t)

Shipping to UK:
$91.79 》 $88.79 (s: $8.95, t: $14.79)

Hoping this might help you lovelies save a few $ in the future 🤍

One thing that I noticed was that the UK breakdown included shipping and tax, for HC I only had shipping.

I also could not check out in USD for HC while I was logged in, but I could if I did so 'as a guest'.

When I did I got both shipping & tax
Broken down s: $36.4, t: $25.21

So, my prices for the set in & delivered to:
My currency, HC: $68.86
My currency, UK: $66.59

Currency USD
HC: $65
UK: $65

Might not be a huge difference in this case, but why pay more than you need.

Weird that the price isn't the same and isn't the same as the $ price listed either, right?

Well, no, not really. This is because the site/service doesn't necessarily use the same conversion as your bank.

So let's not let the site do the conversion, set the currency to USD.

I live in europe and if I would have gone ahead without any of this I would have payed $132.42, broken down as price: $68.86 + shipping: $63.56.

Now, I have family in the UK and was curious what they would pay.

Price: $66.59, shipping: $9.84, tax: $15.36.

Let me preface this by saying:

1. I love H 🤍
2. Currency conversion can be weird
3. Most of this is handled by 3rd party services - not the site
4. This is perfectly legal
5. Examples are from my personal experience with buying the set using a foreign currency converted to USD

Since not all of this seems to be common knowledge I thought I would share some tips on making sure you are getting the best price when shopping online 🤍
